collections.description: The Allen Coral Atlas is a global-scale coral reef habitat mapping project using Planet Dove 3.7m resolution daily satellite imagery, wave models, and ecological data to create consistent global coral reef habitat maps supporting science and conservation. The Allen Coral Atlas collection consists of four complementary datasets: reef extent which provides the overall boundary of reef environments visible from satellites, geomorphic zones which maps the physical structure of reefs (slopes, crests, flats, etc.), benthic habitats which characterizes the seafloor cover types (coral/algae, sand, rubble, etc.), and mapped regions which defines the geographic boundaries that have been analyzed.

collections.description: Comprehensive dataset collection revealing an extensive and previously unknown reef system at the Amazon River mouth. The collection includes data from multidisciplinary surveys conducted between 2010-2014 that discovered a significant carbonate system spanning approximately 9,500 km between French Guiana and Brazil. The datasets document reef structures, rhodolith beds, sponge communities, and fishing activities, along with oceanographic measurements and the seasonal influence of the Amazon River plume. This collection provides crucial baseline data about reef ecosystems functioning under marginal conditions, with implications for understanding reef systems' responses to climate change.

collections.description: The purpose of Marine Regions is to create a standard, relational list of geographic names, coupled with information and maps of the geographic location of these features. The objectives are to capture all geographic marine names worldwide, including ocean basins, seas, seamounts, sandbanks, ridges, bays and other marine geographical place names and attributes, and to display univocally the boundaries of marine biogeographic or other managed marine areas in order to facilitate marine data management, marine (bio)geographic research and the management of marine areas. Marine Regions is freely available at MarineRegions.org. Marine Regions is managed by Flanders Marine Institute. The Marine Regions database builds further on an integration of the VLIMAR Gazetteer (place names) and the VLIZ Maritime Boundaries Geodatabase (polygons for sea areas). Funding for the creation of the VLIMAR gazetteer was provided initially through the EU Network of Excellence MarBEF, funding for the further development and maintenance of Marine Regions is provided by Research Foundation - Flanders (FWO) as part of the Belgian contribution to LifeWatch.

collections.description: GEBCOs current gridded bathymetric data set, the GEBCO_2025 Grid, is a global terrain model for ocean and land, providing elevation data, in meters, on a 15 arc-second interval grid. This release also includes a version of the grid with under-ice topography/bathymetry information for Greenland and Antarctica.

collections.description: Seamounts are isolated elevations in the seafloor with circular or elliptical plans, comparatively steep slopes, and relatively small summit area (Menard, 1964). The vertical gravity gradient (VGG), which is the curvature of the ocean surface topography derived from satellite altimeter measurements, has been used to map the global distribution of seamounts (Kim & Wessel, 2011). We used the latest grid of VGG to update and refine the global seamount catalog; we identified 19325 new seamounts, expanding a previously published catalog having 24643 seamounts.
collections.title: Global Distribution and Morphology of Small Seamounts (Gevorgian et al. 2023)

collections.description: The Global Mangrove Watch Version 3.0 represents the most comprehensive record of global mangrove change achieved to date and is expected to support a wide range of activities, including the ongoing monitoring of the global coastal environment, defining and assessments of progress towards conservation targets, protected area planning and risk assessments of mangrove ecosystems worldwide. This study utilized L-band Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) datasets from JAXA to develop a global time-series of mangrove extent and change from 1996 to 2020, revealing a 3.4% loss in mangrove coverage over 24 years, with findings contributing to global environmental monitoring and conservation efforts.

collections.description: This dataset presents mapped localities of marine nature types in Norway, as identified by the Norwegian Environment Agency following the criteria in DN-hndbok 19 (revised 2007). Each site is assigned a scientific value (A: very important, B: important, C: locally important) based on size, condition, and biodiversity. The dataset covers areas both within and outside legally protected zones, supporting environmental impact assessments and land-use planning. Mapping began in 2000 in collaboration with the Directorate of Fisheries, with ongoing improvements in data precision and modeling. Some key shellfish habitats are also included as nature type data for practical reasons. The dataset was previously published as Naturtyper - DN-hndbok 19 and offers detailed area descriptions to explain value assessments.

collections.description: The Nansen Legacy is a novel and holistic Arctic research project providing integrated scientific knowledge on the rapidly changing marine climate and ecosystem. A new knowledge base is required to facilitate a sustainable management of the northern Barents Sea and adjacent Arctic Basin through the 21st century. The Nansen Legacy JC3 cruise (Feb 19-Mar 11,2022) aimed to address gaps in winter-to-spring transition data in the Nansen Basin, focusing on joint physical, chemical, and biological sampling, revealing thin ice and a winter-mode ecosystem despite prominent warm Atlantic water

collections.description: This study presents the first digital seafloor geomorphic features map (GSFM) of the global ocean. The GSFM includes 131,192 separate polygons in 29 geomorphic feature categories, used here to assess differences between passive and active continental margins as well as between 8 major ocean regions (the Arctic, Indian, North Atlantic, North Pacific, South Atlantic, South Pacific and the Southern Oceans and the Mediterranean and Black Seas). The GSFM provides quantitative assessments of differences between passive and active margins: continental shelf width of passive margins (88km) is nearly three times that of active margins (31km); the average width of active slopes (36km) is less than the average width of passive margin slopes (46km); active margin slopes contain an area of 3.4millionkm2 where the gradient exceeds 5, compared with 1.3millionkm2 on passive margin slopes; the continental rise covers 27millionkm2 adjacent to passive margins and less than 2.3millionkm2 adjacent to active margins. Examples of specific applications of the GSFM are presented to show that: 1) larger rift valley segments are generally associated with slow-spreading rates and smaller rift valley segments are associated with fast spreading; 2) polar submarine canyons are twice the average size of non-polar canyons and abyssal polar regions exhibit lower seafloor roughness than non-polar regions, expressed as spatially extensive fan, rise and abyssal plain sediment deposits  all of which are attributed here to the effects of continental glaciations; and 3) recognition of seamounts as a separate category of feature from ridges results in a lower estimate of seamount number compared with estimates of previous workers.
collections.title: Seafloor Geomorphic Features Map

collections.description: This data collection, originally published on the Oceans Futures platform, is designed to provide early warning about future conflict over marine fisheries under climate change through chronic risk analysis. Fisheries conflict is a dispute over access to a fisheries resource, broadly defined. That conflict can be non-violent or violent. It can involve individual actors (e.g., fisherfolk), entire fishing communities, fishing vessels active at sea, enforcement actors (e.g., marine park rangers or Coast Guards acting on anti-illegal fishing patrols), or even militaries (e.g., naval vessels). Conflict may result in no actions, changes in policies, arrests and detentions, abductions or kidnapping, the confiscation of fishing gear of fish catch, fatalities, and the potential for fractures in diplomatic or economic relations between nations. The collection includes comprehensive datasets covering EEZ risk assessments, species distributions, temperature scenarios, and regional conflict hotspots, supported by detailed technical documentation of methods and analysis.
collections.title: WWF Oceans Futures - Fisheries Conflict Risk Assessment

collections.description: This collection contains global marine seabed substrate mappings at 0.1 degree (nominally 11km) resolution based on the dbSEABED global seabed observation database, currently containing approximatly 6 million observations over all zones of the oceans. dbSEABED creates unified, detailed mappings of the materials that make the seafloor by efficiently integrating tens of thousands of individual datasets. The goal is to bring decades of seabed information - and today's latest information - from marine geology, biology, engineering and surveys into one seabed mapping that can fulfil the community needs for ocean-bottom information on many spatial scales. The system deals with the material textures, compositions, strengths, colours, features, geology and biology.
collections.title: dbSEABED: Global Mappings of Seafloor Substrates
